Introduction

Giant unilamellar vesicles (GUVs) are spherical

shells, S-ZOO pm in diameter, composed of a single lipid

bilayer (Figure 1). In contrast to their smaller cousins (i.e.

the 30-50 nm ‘small unilamellar

vesicle’ and

the 100-200 nm ‘large unilamellar vesicle’), the GUV can

be seen under the light microscope, and therein lies its

most important attribute. Since GUVs are visible, various

morphological changes (such as budding, healing, endocy-

tosis, and other ‘cytomimetic’ processes) can be viewed

and monitored as directly as they can using living cells. Yet

GUVs have an advantage over living cells in that the mem-

brane composition is systematically controllable. One can,

for instance, ask how the rate of healing of a damaged

membrane depends upon the cholesterol content of the

bilayer, a question that is, for all practical purposes, unan-

swerable when dealing with living systems. As a result of

the microscopic visibility of giant vesicles in water, they

are becoming increasingly important in investigations of

biomembranes; hence the review.

