Two final issues may be raised by way of introduction: style and organization. The style of this review is terse (in tribute to those who wish to obtain the essence of the field as quickly as possible). Lack of a smooth discursive text (favored by us in the past) is further necessitated by a page limitation and, as we shall see, by the diverse expertise that has been applied to the giant vesicle problem. Organization-wise, we have subdivided recent papers into four categories: membrane physics, chemical aspects, biochemical interactions, and cytomimetic phenomena. Often there is considerable overlap, and the assignment of a paper to a category is somewhat arbitrary. Indeed, the selection of the papers themselves is somewhat arbitrary. Fortunately, at this early stage of development, it is preferable to stimulate the imagination than to blanket the subject.
Membrane physics Giant vesicles possess fluid membranes that assume an amazing variety of shapes according to the nature of the lipid molecules and the physical environment. For example, small temperature changes can induce budding. Seifert [4] has written a monograph describing a systematic physical theory of the static and dynamic aspects of vesicle configurations. Preferred vesicle shapes arise from a competition between curvature energy, geometrical constraints (e.g. surface area and volume), osmotic pressure, and bilayer characteristics. Dynamic fluctuations are governed by factors such as viscous damping (i.e. the

