Also found in the recent physics literature is a paper by Dabereiner et al. [S], who developed and experimentally tested the so-called ‘area difference elasticity’ (ADE) model of vesicle shapes. Using video-phase contrast microscopy, the authors recorded the two-dimensional contours for individual phospholipid giant vesicles as a function of temperature. Particular attention was given to prolate vesicles which, upon heating, experienced a mechanical instability leading to budding. Crude but satisfactory agreement was found between ADE theory and the temperature at which instability occurs, as well as the geometry of the budded shape.

What is the essence of this ADE model? The shape of a fluid bilayer vesicle is controlled by two terms: a bending energy and the area difference between two leaflets of a bilayer (the outer leaflet, of course, having the greater area). The area difference is determined by the difference in the number of lipid molecules in the inner and outer leaflets. In the equilibrium (relaxed) state, the area per molecule depends upon the type of lipid and the temperature. ‘Flip-flopping’ of a molecule from one leaflet to another is, incidentally, too slow a process to interfere with the analysis on the time-scale of vesicle fluctuations. In order for a vesicle to assume a new shape, elastic energy is necessary to force the area difference between the leaflets to depart from the relaxed value. Since the vesicle is in the fluid state, the elastic energy is distributed uniformly over the entire vesicle surface. Simplifying the situation, and neglecting all mathematics, one can state that it is possible to estimate both the bending energy and the elastic energy required to distort a bilayer at any particular temperature. Thus, the Dabereiner et al. [S] article gives what seems to be the first direct “quantitative confrontation between theory and experiment”.
An article by Wintz etal. [6] on ‘starfish vesicles’ should be mentioned here in order to drive home an important point. When GUV systems are subjected to osmotic deflation via addition of glucose to the external water, the vesicles (now two to three times smaller in volume) assume ‘starfish’ shapes with as many as seven arms (Figure 2). Although the starfish vesicles are nonaxisymmetric in shape, it can be shown that they comprise axisymmetric subunits (i.e. a core, cylindrical arms, and spherical caps at the end of each arm). The various shapes can be predicted by minimizing curvature under geometrical constraints. Most important, however, is the fact that there exists a multitude of locally stable starfish that have different appearances but almost the same energy as one another. The distribution and inter-

