Reflection interference contrast microscopy (RICM) is a

valuable, new method for measuring the adhesion of giant

vesicles to membranes. The method was introduced in an

article by Nardi et al. [8], who constructed a supported

membrane with the following layers (from bottom to top):

a glass coverslide; a 95 nm-thick MgF, layer (to enhance

RICM sensitivity); a 2.5 pm-thick SiO, film rendered

hydrophobic with octadecyltrichlorosilane;

a polymer

‘cushion’ comprising six layers (deposited by the

Langmuir-Blodgett

technique) of a poly(alkyl-L-gluta-

mate) copolymer; and a phosphatidylcholine monolayer

containing a pH-sensitive anionic amphiphile. The com-

plex assembly is portrayed in Figure 3. When a positively

charged GUV adheres to the negatively charged mem-

brane and is illuminated from below, light is reflected back

from both the MgF, and the GUV surfaces, thereby creat-

ing interference patterns that allow visualization of the

contact zone.

What kind of information does the RICM-based method provide? The most striking observation is a transition from a homogeneous contact area into a pattern of circular, brightly lit patches (called ‘blisters’). Blister formation occurs only if the charge density in the opposing membranes differs significantly (e.g. 1 mole% cationic lipid in the GUV and 10 mole% anionic amphiphile in the supported membrane). As the pH of the aqueous medium is increased from 4.2 to 4.5, the pHsensitive amphiphile in the membrane becomes more anionic, and the blisters grow in size and number. Although the blisters appear to be ‘decoupled’ (i.e. free to escape the area of formation), there remain regions of tight adhesion, where electrostatic membrane-membrane attraction persists. Stabilization of these blisters can be rationalized by Parsegian-Gingell theory [9], insomuch as counterion accumulation in the contact area imparts neutrality.

Dietrich et al. [lo] examined the statics and dynamics of adhesion between a latex sphere and a giant vesicle. The subject is relevant to the understanding of how colloidalsized entities penetrate cell membranes, as would occur, for example, in drug vectorization based on microparticles. Thus, a solid latex sphere, a few microns in diameter, was brought into contact with a much larger phospholipid GUV with the aid of an optical trap. Thereupon, the small latex particle jumps out of the optical trap and adheres to the membrane bilayer (Figure 4), an event observable by video light microscopy. Initially, the particle localizes itself within the membrane such that a portion of the sphere remains outside the membrane while the remainder, coated with lipid, penetrates internally (a process called ‘partial wetting’). Although the particle can be optically pushed through the fluid membrane to any point on the GUV, pulling the particle, using the optical trap, in a direction opposite the vesicle center causes the entire particle-vesicle complex to move as a whole. Adhesion is followed by a second step, called ‘partial ingestion’, in which the particle, now totally coated with lipid, crosses the membrane barrier and enters the vesicle interior, where it situates itself adjacent to the inside membrane surface. Since a reduction in vesicle size is observed, it is believed that ingestion causes the formation of a pore through which internal water flows into the bulk water. Once a particle has been ingested, it can move back and forth (i.e. in expulsion and recapture steps). The remarkable sequence of adhesion, ingestion, expulsion, and recapture occurs within 100 seconds.
