The presence of lipid-grafted PEG (molecular weight [MW] = 750 kDa) inhibited the partitioning of MOPC micelles into the membrane. On the other hand, up to 20 mole% of PEG-lipid failed to affect the exchange of MOPC monomer in and out of the GUV membrane. Thus, the experimental data, buttressed by theoretical considerations, show that the grafted PEG acts as an effective molecular ‘filter’; the polymer sterically blocks larger entities, such as micelles, but not single molecules, from reaching the membrane. In the absence of PEG, the MOPC micelles can solubilize the GUVs. These results are relevant to the so-called ‘stealth’ effect-the protection of vesicles by PEG against cellular uptake when injected into the bloodstream.
Recently, Ueda et al. [K?] have coated phospholipid giant vesicles with hydrophobized polysaccharide, a work that represents the first direct observation of a cell-wall mimic using GUV technology. By covering the entire outside surface of

GUVs with polysaccharide, one can impede self-aggregation of the vesicles and thus have better control of the external conditions (pH, ionic strength, etc.). The coated GUVs were prepared as follows: a fluorescent probe (fluorescein isothiocyanate) was covalently attached to a cholesteryl-bearing pullulan molecule (MW = 55,000 kDa; 1.2 cholesterol groups per 100 sugar units). This material, admixed with a common phospholipid, was converted by the hydration method [l] into giant vesicles, which were examined by fluorescence and laser confocal microscopies. It is quite clear from the images that the sugar covers uniformly and completely the outer surface of the GUVs. Apparently, the cholesteryl substituents, known to have an affinity for bilayers, ‘nail’ the hydrophobic pullulan molecules to the membrane.
More and more people are using ‘electroformation’, developed by Angelova and Dimitrov [13], to prepare GUVs 30-60 pm in diameter. In this method (also detailed in [3]), a lipid film deposited on a platinum wire or a metal-coated glass plate is swelled in the presence of an external AC field. The resulting GUVs are perfectly spherical, relatively monodisperse, and probably unilamellar. Moreover, the electroformation apparatus can be obtained at modest cost. A good example of the experiments with electroformed GUVs was published by Mathivet etal. [14]. They showed that freshly made phospholipid GUVs are under high surface tension and therefore the vesicles show no surface undulations. Thermal undulations could be triggered, however, by the following: incubation at 40°C for 20 hours, a treatment that is believed to lead to the formation of lysolipids (i.e. lipids that have lost a chain via hydrolysis); and application of a 20 mM excess external concentration of sucrose. Undulation is a common phenomenon among chemically deflated giant vesicles.
