Biochemical interactions Talin is a protein comprising a 47 kDa amino-terminal domain with an affinity for membrane attachment, and a 190 kDa carboxy-terminal domain rich in a helix. It seems that the amino terminus can penetrate into the bilayer and create a hole in the membrane. The hole edge is covered with talin such that the amino-terminal domains are associated with the newly exposed lipid chains, while the more hydrophilic carboxy-terminal domains reach out into the external water. The morphological transformation was observed by high-intensity dark-field microscopy [17]. Thus, upon addition of up to 2 PM talin, a spherical unilamellar GUV immediately opened up into a cup-shaped object. As the hole within the GUV grew progressively, the GUV deteriorated into a bilayer sheet. Remarkably, the bilayer sheet reverted back to a spherical GUV when the talin was diluted, indicating that the massive structural change is reversible.

