Fully or partially solubilized amphiphiles can have a substantial effect upon the bending stiffness of giant vesicles as shown in work by Hgckl et al. [16]. For example, only 1 mole% of valinomycin (a cyclic peptide) within the phospholipid membrane reduces the membrane stiffness (i.e. its bending elastic modulus) by a factor of two. This contrasts with the relative insensitivity of stiffness to the nature of the phospholipid (e.g. its degree of unsaturation or chain length). One explanation postulates that valinomycin (or a transient cluster of valinomycin within the bilayer) creates local thinning of the membrane that increases the vesicle flaccidity. Alternatively, the valinomycin might induce a local spontaneous curvature and thereby decrease effective bending rigidity.

Most recent work involving enzyme-GUV interactions has been carried out by Luisi, Walde and co-workers [18], one example of which will be given here. Femtoliter amounts of snake venom phospholipase A, were microinjected onto or into lo-60 pm GUVs composed of phospholipid bilayers. Phospholipase A, is an enzyme that hydrolytically removes the chain two of phospholipids, rendering the compound incapable of bilayer formation. Not surprisingly, external injection of the enzyme upon the giant vesicles caused them to burst. In contrast, however, microinjection inside the GUVs resulted in a slow and constant decrease in vesicle size until the vesicle eventually disappeared from the resolution power of the light microscope. The source of the difference between external and internal injection is not completely clear. One possibility is that the external injection releases enzyme at high concentration at a specific region on the GUV surface; the resulting localized damage causes the vesicle to burst. Internal injection, on the other hand, may spread the enzyme more uniformly over the entire inside leaflet. Another possibility is that the difference between external and internal injection stems from the ability of the hydrolyzed lipid to diffuse away from the vesicle only on external injection.

Soltesz and Hammer [19] found that a wild type fusion

peptide from influenza virus (X31) induces a pH-depen-

dent lysis of giant vesicles. The rate and extent of lysis

reach their maxima at pH 5. Neither the size of the GUVs,

nor their preparation-dependent

tension, seems to affect

the lysis rate. No fusion was observed in the presence

of X31, even when two vesicles were brought into contact

(it being unclear, of course, whether the vesicles were truly

contacting each other at the molecular level). Later

work [ZO] showed that a viral fusion protein inserts into the

bilayer, increases the membrane area, and causes porous

defects within the membrane.

