A giant vesicle composed of didodecyldimethylammonium bromide was irradiated at the periphery by Kitamura et al. [Zl] using a focused laser beam (at a wavelength of 1064 nm, using several hundred milliwatts of power). Video photomicroscopy revealed giant vesicle transformation and fission that was promoted by the radiation pressure. Thus, the spherical vesicle first because ellipsoidal. The structure further deformed into an elongated entity that pinched off into two discrete bodies: a small spherical vesicle and a larger ellipsoidal vesicle (Figure 7). With the laser turned off, this ellipsoid vesicle reformed into a sphere within a few seconds. Optically induced deformation is attributed to a ‘pinning effect’ (i.e. the irradiated portion of the bilayer at the laser focus remains fixed in position, while the remainder of the bilayer undulates according to its viscous resistance and other factors). The result is a distortion of the membrane.

