The induced separation of a binate vesicle into two independent entities was recently reported [ZZ]. A binate vesicle is a vesicle which contains within it a nonconcentric vesicle of almost equal size (Figure 8a). When such a vesicle is exposed to a small osmotic pressure, as created by diluting the system with distilled water, there ensues a process, visualized by phase-contrast microscopy (Figure 8), in which the binate vesicle divides. The separation can be quantified (i.e. volumes and surface areas were measured before and after the osmotic pressure change). It can be shown, for example, that the sum of the volumes of the two particles after dilution exceeds that of the binate’s outer periphery before dilution. Thus, external water must flow into the system. This is evident from Figure 8d, in which the intermediate is flaccid and strongly undulating prior to entry of water (presumably at the juncture gap). An increase in temperature will also stimulate the division of a binate GUV.
